## Theorem: amc12a_2016_p2

Theorem: amc12a_2016_p2
Variables: x (real)
Given: h₀ : (10:ℝ)^x * 100^(2 * x) = 1000^5
Prove: x = 3

Goal: x = 3

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "Rewrite every base as a power of 10, so the equation becomes a single exponential equation in 10 with equal exponents.",
  "plan": [
    "Convert 100 and 1000 into powers of 10.",
    "Use exponent rules to combine the left-hand side into one power of 10.",
    "Rewrite the right-hand side as a power of 10.",
    "Equate exponents and solve for x."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "The given equation is equivalent to 10^x * (10^2)^(2x) = (10^3)^5.",
      "reasoning": "Since 100 = 10^2 and 1000 = 10^3, substituting these identities into the hypothesis preserves equality.",
      "facts_used": [
        "100 = 10^2",
        "1000 = 10^3",
        "substitution into an equation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The left-hand side simplifies to 10^(5x).",
      "reasoning": "Using the power-of-a-power rule, (10^2)^(2x) = 10^(4x). Then multiplying powers with the same base gives 10^x · 10^(4x) = 10^(x+4x) = 10^(5x).",
      "facts_used": [
        "power of a power",
        "product of powers with the same base",
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The right-hand side simplifies to 10^15.",
      "reasoning": "By the power-of-a-power rule, (10^3)^5 = 10^(3·5) = 10^15.",
      "facts_used": [
        "power of a power",
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "10^(5x) = 10^15.",
      "reasoning": "From steps 1–3, both sides of the original equation simplify to these powers of 10, so they must be equal.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 2",
        "step 3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "5x = 15.",
      "reasoning": "The exponential function with base 10 is injective on real exponents, so equal powers of 10 have equal exponents.",
      "facts_used": [
        "injectivity of exponential function with base 10",
        "step 4"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "x = 3.",
      "reasoning": "Dividing the equation 5x = 15 by 5 gives x = 3.",
      "facts_used": [
        "algebraic division",
        "step 5"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "3"
}

